tr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0097"><gtr:id>D42A2FAB-583A-4D34-A223-F037E7EF2473</gtr:id><gtr:title>Instrument Choice for Agriculture and Environment Policy - Development of Systematic (Algebraic) Framework and Decision Support Model</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0097</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The overall aim of the project is to develop a systematic (algebraic) framework that can be used to assess the most suitable choice of instrument for a given environmental goal. The most suitable instrument can be defined as the instrument that achieves this goal with the minimum social cost incurred. Such a framework would have to take into consideration the decision-making process of the farmer, the monitoring and enforcement requirements for the possible instruments and the costs to the public sector. Alongside this will run certain constraints, including legal and political constraints. Within this framework, consideration will have to be given to less tangible factors that influence the decision-making process of a farmer. On a basic level a farmer will comply with a regulation or meet with the requirements for claiming a subsidy if the costs of doing so are smaller than the costs incurred with non-compliance. However, the 'costs' to a farmer will be more than pecuniary and may relate to factors such as a moral desire to follow the letter of the law or a natural risk aversion. The project will predominantly focus on empirical modelling and measurement to provide policy makers with an empirically informed instrument choice.&lt;/p>

